<p><b>The unit for the numbers in bars is articles.</b> Since Wikipedia is based on the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Wide_Web" title="World Wide Web">Web</a> and therefore worldwide, contributors to the same language edition may use different dialects or may come from different countries (as is the case for the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_Wikipedia" title="English Wikipedia">English edition</a>). These differences may lead to some conflicts over <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_and_British_English_spelling_differences" title="American and British English spelling differences">spelling differences</a> (e.g. <i>colour</i> versus <i><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Color" title="Color">color</a></i>)<sup id="cite_ref-WP_spelling_MOS_1_98-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_spelling_MOS_1-98"><span>[</span>96<span>]</span></a></sup> or points of view.<sup id="cite_ref-WP_countering_bias_1_99-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_countering_bias_1-99"><span>[</span>97<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Though the various language editions are held to global policies such as "neutral point of view", they diverge on some points of policy and practice, most notably on whether images that are not <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_content" title="Free content">licensed freely</a> may be used under a claim of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fair_use" title="Fair use">fair use</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-WP_meta_fair_use_1_100-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_meta_fair_use_1-100"><span>[</span>98<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-WP_meta_WP_images_1_101-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_meta_WP_images_1-101"><span>[</span>99<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-IBM_visual_WP_1_102-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IBM_visual_WP_1-102"><span>[</span>100<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Jimmy Wales has described Wikipedia as "an effort to create and distribute a free encyclopedia of the highest possible quality to every single person on the planet in their own language".<sup id="cite_ref-WP_Wales_free_multi-lingual_encyclopedia_103-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_Wales_free_multi-lingual_encyclopedia-103"><span>[</span>101<span>]</span></a></sup> Though each language edition functions more or less independently, some efforts are made to supervise them all. They are coordinated in part by Meta-Wiki, the Wikimedia Foundation's wiki devoted to maintaining all of its projects (Wikipedia and others).<sup id="cite_ref-WP_metawiki_maintenance_1_104-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_metawiki_maintenance_1-104"><span>[</span>102<span>]</span></a></sup> For instance, Meta-Wiki provides important statistics on all language editions of Wikipedia,<sup id="cite_ref-WP_meta_stats_1_105-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_meta_stats_1-105"><span>[</span>103<span>]</span></a></sup> and it maintains a list of articles every Wikipedia should have.<sup id="cite_ref-WP_meta_articles_on_all_sites_1_106-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_meta_articles_on_all_sites_1-106"><span>[</span>104<span>]</span></a></sup> The list concerns basic content by subject: biography, history, geography, society, culture, science, technology, and mathematics. As for the rest, it is not rare for articles strongly related to a particular language not to have counterparts in another edition. For example, articles about small towns in the United States might only be available in English, even when they meet notability criteria of other language Wikipedia projects.</p>
